Semilarski v. prosecutor’s office: the cassation of former deputy mayor of Tartu will be considered on 4 August
This means that the decision on it is likely to be made in early September.
The courts of the first two instances refused to consider Semilarski's case, but in April his appeal was accepted by the State Court.
On 12 December 2019, the Tartu Administrative Court returned the complaint to the applicant, as its authorisation does not fall within the jurisdiction of the administrative court.
The court ' s ruling stated that the complaint contained a claim for compensation for damages caused in the course of criminal proceedings.
“Such matters should be regulated by the prosecutor’s office and the court of departure,” Anette Kreatsmann, the press secretary of the Tartu courts, told ERR correspondent.
According to her, Valvo Semilarski appealed this decision to the district court, which on 5 February did not change the decision of the court of first instance.
Now the judge will have to say his word.
According to lawyer Semilarski, a jury lawyer for Oliver Neaes, his client was unjustifiably suspected of bribery for about two years.
He now demands that the prosecutor’s office refute false claims to his address and compensate him for moral damages.
The reason for the complaint to the court was the statements made by the prosecutor on special cases of the district prosecutor’s office of Margus Gross, made by him in October 2017, when Semilarski, together with another at the time Deputy Mayor of Tartu Prestulek Artem Suvorov was detained on suspicion of suspicion.
“When I was arrested, the security police and the prosecutor’s office immediately organized a press conference and informed the entire Republic of Estonia that the Tartu leaders – one of the most influential bodies of local self-government – were selling.
These airborne public suspicions have accompanied me for about two years.
And now that these allegations and suspicions were false, the prosecutor’s office doesn’t want to say anything about it,” Semilarski said in early August 2019.
According to Oliver Nyas, at a press conference, the prosecutor went beyond the legal framework in which the prosecutor’s office should act.
“The allegations of bribery and forgery were false, but that’s not the only problem here.
The European Court of Human Rights, for example, has repeatedly stressed in its rulings on Russia and Lithuania that at the stage of the investigation, representatives of the State should be careful when choosing words so that the suspects are not represented as criminals before the sentence is handed down.
To this the prosecutor’s office also owes a presumption of innocence, which, unfortunately, was not respected in this case against Valvo Semilarski,” said Nyas.
"Public representation of Semilarski as a serious offender and perpetrator in circumstances where the facts underlying the suspicion of bribery are still found to be inadmissible, which contradicts the presumption of innocence and is unjust in relation to claims," he said.
As wrote by rus.err.ee, former deputy mayor of Tartu Valvo Semilarski will not be held liable for charges of bribery - the criminal case brought against him in July was partially closed.
At the same time, a former official is tried on charges of knowingly violating anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions in particularly large quantities.
According to the indictment, in the period from 2015 to 2017, the former deputy mayor of Tartu participated more than thirty times in the meetings of the city administration in making decisions related to the companies operating in Tartu, with the owners or managers of which Semilarski actively communicated in person.
According to Gross, in all these cases, Semilarsky had personal interests, and therefore he had to refrain from participating in decision-making.
Earlier, as wrote rus.err.ee, the prosecutor’s office has raised suspicions of receiving bribery and violating anti-corruption legislation when conducting transactions in particularly large quantities.
This happened in October 2016, when he was arrested along with another deputy mayor, Artem Suvorov (Centrist Party).
The prosecutor’s office and the security police said there was strong evidence against both deputy mayors.
After that, both officials resigned.
Suvorov’s case later came to a court that fully justified politics.
The case of Valvo Semilarski is pending.
